    <title>Combined summary - Signature Blocks and URI Sign Requests</title>
    <updated>2023-06-06T03:57:48.787901+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2012-April/001362.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin community is engaging in discussions to improve the security and efficiency of Bitcoin transactions. One topic of discussion is the use of existing standards instead of creating new solutions to avoid unnecessary complexity. Gavin Andresen suggests using S/MIME or other "sign a message" standards to encode signature blocks or BIP-10 transactions. Alan Reiner clarifies that he is proposing an intermediate data format that allows users to sign messages with their existing Bitcoin identities, rather than changes to the Bitcoin protocol itself.While some members suggest using PGP/EC for signing and verifying messages due to its existing web-of-trust and keyserver infrastructure, others express concern about adding too many features to Bitcoin. The need for simplicity and caution when considering changes to the protocol is emphasized.In addition, the conversation highlights the importance of improved security measures within Bitcoin transactions. Multi-sig technology is recognized as critical, and proposals are made to execute them in fewer steps for user adoption. Proposed solutions include Signature Blocks, Sign-Message URI scheme, and defining URL signing/authentication itself.A debate on the sign-request URI and its relation to the existing bitcoin: URI scheme also takes place among members. While Gavin Andresen suggests extending existing standards, Peter argues against adding PGP's web of trust to Bitcoin, suggesting that simplicity should be added to the protocol design instead.Overall, the conversations suggest a thoughtful and pragmatic approach to innovation in the field of digital security by leveraging existing standards and technologies while advocating for an efficient and effective way forward in developing new tools and systems.</summary>
